 <link>
comedy thriller</link> film in which the eponymous Gerald Arthur Otley, a hapless and light-fingered <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../477/346477.xml">
antique</link>s dealer played by <actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../366/163366.xml">
Tom Courtenay</link></actor>
, is mistaken for a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/10501.xml">
spy</link> and grows into the part - to such an extent that the real spy played by <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../224/154224.xml">
Romy Schneider</link></actor>
</person>
 falls for him. The action - one hesitates to say plot - romps from one stereotypical English situation to another: <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../413/5476413.xml">
Rolls Royce</link>s are driven, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/29969.xml">
tea</link> is drunk, and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../085/1962085.xml">
bacon sandwich</link>es are fried and thrown to the dogs.<p>

The locations and situations are a catalogue of England in the 60s and are lovingly stuffed with period detail: a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../928/1031928.xml">
houseboat</link> colony on the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../031/49031.xml">
Thames</link>, clubs - <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../918/3715918.xml">
Playboy</link></institution>
</company>
 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../299/7367299.xml">
health</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../970/867970.xml">
golf</link>, an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../857/18993857.xml">
explosion</link> in <artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<facility wordnetid="103315023" confidence="0.8">
<station wordnetid="104306080" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../581/181581.xml">
Notting Hill Gate tube station</link></station>
</facility>
</artifact>
, a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../613/972613.xml">
driving test</link> taken in a <car wordnetid="102958343" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../897/230897.xml">
Vauxhall Viva</link></car>
 that turns into a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../685/1000685.xml">
car chase</link> with a <car wordnetid="102958343" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../991/841991.xml">
Ford Zephyr</link></car>
 (or Zodiac), a pile-up of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../627/23627.xml">
